depth of field">DOF</abbr> in counterintuitive ways. Because the circle of =
confusion is directly tied to the sensor size, decreasing the size of the s=
ensor while holding focal length and aperture constant will <em>decrease</e=
m> the depth of field (by the crop factor). The resulting image will also h=
ave a different field of view. If, however, the focal length is altered to =
maintain the original field of view, while holding the aperture constant, t=
he <abbr title=3D"depth of field">DOF</abbr> will remain constant.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Depth_of_field#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth_of_field#cite_note-7=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth_of_field#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth_o=
f_field#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Effect_of_lens_aperture">Ef=
fect of lens aperture</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DDepth_of_field&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit s=
ection: Effect of lens aperture"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>For a given subject framing and camera position, the <abbr title=3D"dept=
h of field">DOF</abbr> is controlled by the lens aperture diameter, which i=
s usually specified as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F-numbe=
r" title=3D"F-number">f-number</a> (the ratio of lens focal length to apert=
ure diameter). Reducing the aperture diameter (increasing the <span class=
=3D"nowrap">f-number</span>) increases the <abbr title=3D"depth of field">D=
OF</abbr> because only the light travelling at shallower angles passes thro=
ugh the aperture so only cones of rays with shallower angles reach the imag=
e plane. In other words, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circl=
e_of_confusion" title=3D"Circle of confusion">circles of confusion</a> are =
reduced or increasing the <abbr title=3D"depth of field">DOF</abbr>.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Depth_of_field#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>For a given size of the subject's image in the focal plane, the same=
 <span class=3D"nowrap">f-number</span> on any focal length lens will give =
the same depth of field.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth_of_field#cite_note-11"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 This is evident from the above <abbr title=3D"depth of field">DOF</abbr> e=
quation by noting that the ratio <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>u</i>/<i>f</i><=
/span> is constant for constant image size. For example, if the focal lengt=
h is doubled, the subject distance is also doubled to keep the subject imag=
e size the same. This observation contrasts with the common notion that "fo=
cal length is twice as important to defocus as f/stop",<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth_of_f=
ield#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> which applies to a constant subject distance=
, as opposed to constant image size.
</p><p>Motion pictures make limited use of aperture control; to produce a c=
onsistent image quality from shot to shot, cinematographers usually choose =
a single aperture setting for interiors (e.g., scenes inside a building) an=
d another for exteriors (e.g., scenes in an area outside a building), and a=
djust exposure through the use of camera filters or light levels. Aperture =
settings are adjusted more frequently in still photography, where variation=
s in depth of field are used to produce a variety of special effects.
</p>
