<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Effect_of_circle_of_confusi=
on">Effect of circle of confusion</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/w/index.php?title=3DDepth_of_field&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" tit=
le=3D"Edit section: Effect of circle of confusion"><span>edit</span></a><sp=
an class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Precise focus is only possible at an exact distance from a lens;<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Depth_of_field#cite_note-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>a<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> at that distance, a point object=
 will produce a small spot image. Otherwise, a point object will produce a =
larger or blur spot image that is typically and approximately a circle. Whe=
n this circular spot is sufficiently small, it is visually indistinguishabl=
e from a point, and appears to be in focus. The diameter of the largest cir=
cle that is indistinguishable from a point is known as the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acceptable_circle_of_confusion" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Acceptable circle of confusion">acceptable circle of confusion=
</a>, or informally, simply as the circle of confusion.
</p><p>The acceptable circle of confusion depends on how the final image wi=
ll be used. The circle of confusion as 0.25&nbsp;mm for an image viewed fro=
m 25&nbsp;cm away is generally accepted.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTESavazzi=
2011109_15-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Depth_of_field#cite_note-FOOTNOTESavazzi2011109-15"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>For <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/35mm_movie_film" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"35mm movie film">35<span class=3D"nowrap">&nbsp;<=
/span>mm</a> motion pictures, the image area on the film is roughly 22&nbsp=
;mm by 16&nbsp;mm. The limit of tolerable error was traditionally set at 0.=
05&nbsp;mm (0.0020&nbsp;in) diameter, while for <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/16_mm_film" title=3D"16 mm film">16&nbsp;mm film</a>, where t=
he size is about half as large, the tolerance is stricter, 0.025&nbsp;mm (0=
.00098&nbsp;in).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth_of_field#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> More mod=
ern practice for 35&nbsp;mm productions set the circle of confusion limit a=
t 0.025&nbsp;mm (0.00098&nbsp;in).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth_of_field#cite_note-17"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Camera_movements">Camera mo=
vements</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDept=
h_of_field&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Camera=
 movements"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</=
span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/View_camera" title=3D"Vi=
ew camera">View camera</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Til=
t%E2%80%93shift_photography" title=3D"Tilt=E2=80=93shift photography">Tilt=
=E2=80=93shift photography</a></div>
<p>The term "camera movements" refers to swivel (swing and tilt, in modern =
terminology) and shift adjustments of the lens holder and the film holder. =
These features have been in use since the 1800s and are still in use today =
on view cameras, technical cameras, cameras with tilt/shift or perspective =
control lenses, etc. Swiveling the lens or sensor causes the plane of focus=
 (POF) to swivel, and also causes the field of acceptable focus to swivel w=
ith the <abbr title=3D"plane of focus">POF</abbr>; and depending on the <ab=
br title=3D"depth of field">DOF</abbr> criteria, to also change the shape o=
f the field of acceptable focus. While calculations for <abbr title=3D"dept=
h of field">DOF</abbr> of cameras with swivel set to zero have been discuss=
ed, formulated, and documented since before the 1940s, documenting calculat=
ions for cameras with non-zero swivel seem to have begun in 1990.
</p><p>More so than in the case of the zero swivel camera, there are variou=
s methods to form criteria and set up calculations for <abbr title=3D"depth=
 of field">DOF</abbr> when swivel is non-zero. There is a gradual reduction=
 of clarity in objects as they move away from the <abbr title=3D"plane of f=
ocus">POF</abbr>, and at some virtual flat or curved surface the reduced cl=
arity becomes unacceptable. Some photographers do calculations or use table=
s, some use markings on their equipment, some judge by previewing the image=
.
</p><p>When the <abbr title=3D"plane of focus">POF</abbr> is rotated, the n=
ear and far limits of <abbr title=3D"depth of field">DOF</abbr> may be thou=
ght of as wedge-shaped, with the apex of the wedge nearest the camera; or t=
hey may be thought of as parallel to the <abbr title=3D"plane of focus">POF=
</abbr>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMerklinger199349=E2=80=9356_18-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth_of_field#cite=
_note-FOOTNOTEMerklinger199349%E2%80%9356-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-FOOTNOTETillmanns199771_19-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Depth_of_field#cite_note-FOOTNOTETillmanns199771-19"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Object-field_calculation_me=
thods">Object-field calculation methods</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection">=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDepth_of_field&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D=
5" title=3D"Edit section: Object-field calculation methods"><span>edit</spa=
n></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Traditional depth-of-field formulas can be hard to use in practice. As a=
n alternative, the same effective calculation can be done without regard to=
 the focal length and <span class=3D"nowrap">f-number</span>.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-20" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dept=
h_of_field#cite_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>b<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Moritz_von_Rohr" title=3D"Moritz von Rohr">Moritz von Rohr</a> and later=
 Merklinger observe that the effective absolute aperture diameter can be us=
ed for similar formula in certain circumstances.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOT=
EMerklinger1992_21-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Depth_of_field#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMerklinger1992-21"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Moreover, traditional depth-of-field formulas assume equal acceptabl=
e circles of confusion for near and far objects. Merklinger<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-22" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth_=
of_field#cite_note-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>c<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> suggested that distant objects often need=
 to be much sharper to be clearly recognizable, whereas closer objects, bei=
ng larger on the film, do not need to be so sharp.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTN=
OTEMerklinger1992_21-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Depth_of_field#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMerklinger1992-21"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 The loss of detail in distant objects may be particularly noticeable with =
extreme enlargements. Achieving this additional sharpness in distant object=
s usually requires focusing beyond the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Hyperfocal_distance" title=3D"Hyperfocal distance">hyperfocal distance=
</a>, sometimes almost at infinity. For example, if photographing a citysca=
pe with a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bollard_(traffic)" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Bollard (traffic)">traffic bollard</a> in the for=
eground, this approach, termed the <i>object field method</i> by Merklinger=
, would recommend focusing very close to infinity, and stopping down to mak=
e the bollard sharp enough. With this approach, foreground objects cannot a=
lways be made perfectly sharp, but the loss of sharpness in near objects ma=
y be acceptable if recognizability of distant objects is paramount.
</p><p>Other authors such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ansel=
_Adams" title=3D"Ansel Adams">Ansel Adams</a> have taken the opposite posit=
ion, maintaining that slight unsharpness in foreground objects is usually m=
ore disturbing than slight unsharpness in distant parts of a scene.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEAdams198051_23-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth_of_field#cite_note-FOOTNOTEAdams198051-23"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Overcoming_DOF_limitations"=
>Overcoming DOF limitations</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/i=
ndex.php?title=3DDepth_of_field&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D=
"Edit section: Overcoming DOF limitations"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Some methods and equipment allow altering the apparent <abbr title=3D"de=
pth of field">DOF</abbr>, and some even allow the <abbr title=3D"depth of f=
ield">DOF</abbr> to be determined after the image is made. These are based =
or supported by computational imaging processes. For example, <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Focus_stacking" title=3D"Focus stacking">focus =
stacking</a> combines multiple images focused on different planes, resultin=
g in an image with a greater (or less, if so desired) apparent depth of fie=
ld than any of the individual source images. Similarly, in order to <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/3D_reconstruction" title=3D"3D reconstruc=
tion">reconstruct</a> the 3-dimensional shape of an object, a <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth_map" title=3D"Depth map">depth map</a> ca=
n be generated from multiple photographs with different depths of field. Xi=
ong and Shafer concluded, in part, "...<span class=3D"nowrap">&nbsp;</span>=
the improvements on precisions of focus ranging and defocus ranging can lea=
d to efficient shape recovery methods."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth_of_field#cite_note-2=
4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup>
</p><p>Another approach is focus sweep. The focal plane is swept across the=
 entire relevant range during a single exposure. This creates a blurred ima=
ge, but with a convolution kernel that is nearly independent of object dept=
h, so that the blur is almost entirely removed after computational deconvol=
ution. This has the added benefit of dramatically reducing motion blur.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Depth_of_field#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Light_scanning_photomacrogr=
aphy" title=3D"Light scanning photomacrography">Light Scanning Photomacrogr=
aphy</a> (LSP) is another technique used to overcome depth of field limitat=
ions in macro and micro photography. This method allows for high-magnificat=
ion imaging with exceptional depth of field. LSP involves scanning a thin l=
ight plane across the subject that is mounted on a moving stage perpendicul=
ar to the light plane. This ensures the entire subject remains in sharp foc=
us from the nearest to the farthest details, providing comprehensive depth =
of field in a single image. Initially developed in the 1960s and further re=
fined in the 1980s and 1990s, LSP was particularly valuable in scientific a=
nd biomedical photography before digital focus stacking became prevalent.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Depth_of_field#cite_note-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2=
3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Clarke2=
024_27-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dept=
h_of_field#cite_note-Clarke2024-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Other technologies use a combination of lens design and post-process=
ing: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wavefront_coding" title=3D"Wa=
vefront coding">Wavefront coding</a> is a method by which controlled aberra=
tions are added to the optical system so that the focus and depth of field =
can be improved later in the process.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-28" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth_of_field#cite_note-28"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup>
</p><p>The lens design can be changed even more: in colour <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apodization" title=3D"Apodization">apodization</a>=
 the lens is modified such that each colour channel has a different lens ap=
erture. For example, the red channel may be <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-in=
line-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1299860632"><span class=3D"fnum=
ber-fallback"><span class=3D"first-letter">f</span>/2.4</span>, green may b=
e <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles=
:r1299860632"><span class=3D"fnumber-fallback"><span class=3D"first-letter"=
>f</span>/2.4</span>, whilst the blue channel may be <link rel=3D"mw-dedupl=
icated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1299860632"><span clas=
s=3D"fnumber-fallback"><span class=3D"first-letter">f</span>/5.6</span>. Th=
erefore, the blue channel will have a greater depth of field than the other=
 colours. The image processing identifies blurred regions in the red and gr=
een channels and in these regions copies the sharper edge data from the blu=
e channel. The result is an image that combines the best features from the =
different <span class=3D"nowrap">f-numbers</span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTN=
OTEKayMatherWalton2011_29-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Depth_of_field#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKayMatherWalton2011-29"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup>
</p><p>At the extreme, a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plenoptic=
_camera" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Plenoptic camera">plenoptic camera<=
/a> captures <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/4D_light_field" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"4D light field">4D light field</a> information ab=
out a scene, so the focus and depth of field can be altered after the photo=
 is taken.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Diffraction_and_DOF">Diffra=
ction and DOF</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DDepth_of_field&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section:=
 Diffraction and DOF"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diffraction" title=3D"Diffracti=
on">Diffraction</a> causes images to lose sharpness at high <span class=3D"=
nowrap">f-numbers</span> (i.e., narrow aperture stop opening sizes), and he=
nce limits the potential depth of field.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEGibson1=
97564_30-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/De=
pth_of_field#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGibson197564-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> (This effect is=
 not considered in the above formula giving approximate <abbr title=3D"dept=
h of field">DOF</abbr> values.) In general photography this is rarely an is=
sue; because large <span class=3D"nowrap">f-numbers</span> typically requir=
e long exposure times to acquire acceptable image brightness, <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Motion_blur" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mot=
ion blur">motion blur</a> may cause greater loss of sharpness than the loss=
 from diffraction. However, diffraction is a greater issue in close-up phot=
ography, and the overall image sharpness can be degraded as photographers a=
re trying to maximize depth of field with very small apertures.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-FOOTNOTEGibson197553_31-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth_of_field#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGibson197553-31"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTELefkowitz197984_32-0" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth_of_field#cite_note-FOOTNOT=
ELefkowitz197984-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Hansma and Peterson have discussed determining the combined effects =
of defocus and diffraction using a root-square combination of the individua=
l blur spots.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHansma1996_33-0" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth_of_field#cite_note-FOOTNO=
TEHansma1996-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPeterson1996_34-0" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth_of_field=
#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPeterson1996-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Hansma's approach determine=
s the <span class=3D"nowrap">f-number</span> that will give the maximum pos=
sible sharpness; Peterson's approach determines the minimum <span class=3D"=
nowrap">f-number</span> that will give the desired sharpness in the final i=
mage and yields a maximum depth of field for which the desired sharpness ca=
n be achieved.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-35" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth_of_field#cite_note-35"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>d<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In combinat=
ion, the two methods can be regarded as giving a maximum and minimum <span =
class=3D"nowrap">f-number</span> for a given situation, with the photograph=
er free to choose any value within the range, as conditions (e.g., potentia=
l motion blur) permit. Gibson gives a similar discussion, additionally cons=
idering blurring effects of camera lens aberrations, enlarging lens diffrac=
tion and aberrations, the negative emulsion, and the printing paper.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEGibson197564_30-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth_of_field#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGibson197564-30"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-36" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth_of_field#cite_note-36"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>e<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Couzin gave a=
 formula essentially the same as Hansma's for optimal <span class=3D"nowrap=
">f-number</span>, but did not discuss its derivation.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-F=
OOTNOTECouzin1982_37-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Depth_of_field#cite_note-FOOTNOTECouzin1982-37"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Hopkins,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHopkins1955_38-0" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth_of_field#cite_note-FOO=
TNOTEHopkins1955-38"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Stokseth,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEStoks=
eth1969_39-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Depth_of_field#cite_note-FOOTNOTEStokseth1969-39"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and Williams =
and Becklund<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEWilliamsBecklund1989_40-0" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth_of_field#cite_no=
te-FOOTNOTEWilliamsBecklund1989-40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> have discussed the combined=
 effects using the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modulation_tran=
sfer_function" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Modulation transfer function"=
>modulation transfer function</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-41" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth_of_field#cite_note-41"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-42" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth_of_field#cite_note-42"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"DOF_scales">DOF scales</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDepth_of_field&a=
mp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: DOF scales"><span>=
edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Many lenses include scales that indicate the <abbr title=3D"depth of fie=
ld">DOF</abbr> for a given focus distance and <span class=3D"nowrap">f-numb=
er</span>; the 35&nbsp;mm lens in the image is typical. That lens includes =
distance scales in feet and meters; when a marked distance is set opposite =
the large white index mark, the focus is set to that distance. The <abbr ti=
tle=3D"depth of field">DOF</abbr> scale below the distance scales includes =
markings on either side of the index that correspond to <span class=3D"nowr=
ap">f-numbers</span>. When the lens is set to a given <span class=3D"nowrap=
">f-number</span>, the <abbr title=3D"depth of field">DOF</abbr> extends be=
tween the distances that align with the <span class=3D"nowrap">f-number</sp=
an> markings.
</p><p>Photographers can use the lens scales to work backwards from the des=
ired depth of field to find the necessary focus distance and aperture.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTERay1994315_43-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth_of_field#cite_note-FOOTNOTERay1994315-43"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>38<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> For the 35&nbsp;mm lens shown, if it were desired for the <abbr =
title=3D"depth of field">DOF</abbr> to extend from 1&nbsp;m to 2&nbsp;m, fo=
cus would be set so that index mark was centered between the marks for thos=
e distances, and the aperture would be set to <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-=
inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1299860632"><span class=3D"fn=
umber-fallback"><span class=3D"first-letter">f</span>/11</span>.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-44" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/D=
epth_of_field#cite_note-44"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>f<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>On a view camera, the focus and <span class=3D"nowrap">f-number</spa=
n> can be obtained by measuring the depth of field and performing simple ca=
lculations. Some view cameras include <abbr title=3D"depth of field">DOF</a=
bbr> calculators that indicate focus and <span class=3D"nowrap">f-number</s=
pan> without the need for any calculations by the photographer.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-FOOTNOTETillmanns199767-68_45-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth_of_field#cite_note-FOOTNOTETillmanns199767=
-68-45"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTERay1994230-231_46-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth_of_field#cite=
_note-FOOTNOTERay1994230-231-46"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>40<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
