n>.</figcaption></figure>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Optics" title=3D"Optics">opt=
ics</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Photography" title=3D"=
Photography">photography</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hype=
rfocal_distance" title=3D"Hyperfocal distance">hyperfocal distance</a> is a=
 distance from a lens beyond which all objects can be brought into an "acce=
ptable" <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Focus_(optics)" title=3D"F=
ocus (optics)">focus</a>. As the hyperfocal distance is the focus distance =
giving the maximum depth of field, it is the most desirable distance to set=
 the focus of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fixed_focus_lens" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fixed focus lens">fixed-focus camera</a>.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-Hyperfocal_distance_Kingslake1951_47-0" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth_of_field#cite_note-Hyperfo=
cal_distance_Kingslake1951-47"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>41<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The hyperfocal distance is entir=
ely dependent upon what level of sharpness is considered to be acceptable.
</p><p>The hyperfocal distance has a property called "consecutive depths of=
 field", where a lens focused at an object whose distance from the lens is =
at the hyperfocal distance <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style=
:italic;">H</span> will hold a depth of field from <span class=3D"texhtml">=
<i>H</i>/2</span> to infinity, if the lens is focused to <span class=3D"tex=
html"><i>H</i>/2</span>, the depth of field will be from <span class=3D"tex=
html"><i>H</i>/3</span> to <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style=
:italic;">H</span>; if the lens is then focused to <span class=3D"texhtml">=
<i>H</i>/3</span>, the depth of field will be from <span class=3D"texhtml">=
<i>H</i>/4</span> to <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>H</i>/2</span>, etc.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Sutton_(photographer=
)" title=3D"Thomas Sutton (photographer)">Thomas Sutton</a> and George Daws=
on first wrote about hyperfocal distance (or "focal range") in 1867.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Hyperfocal_distance_:0_48-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth_of_field#cite_note-Hyperfocal_distance_:0=
-48"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>42<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> Louis Derr in 1906 may have been the first to derive a for=
mula for hyperfocal distance. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rudo=
lf_Kingslake" title=3D"Rudolf Kingslake">Rudolf Kingslake</a> wrote in 1951=
 about the two methods of measuring hyperfocal distance.
</p>
Some cameras have their hyperfocal distance marked on the focus dial. For e=
xample, on the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minox" title=3D"Min=
ox">Minox</a> LX focusing dial there is a red dot between <span class=3D"no=
wrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7000200000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>2&nbsp;=
m</span> and infinity; when the lens is set at the red dot, that is, focuse=
d at the hyperfocal distance, the depth of field stretches from <span class=
=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7000200000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>2=
&nbsp;m</span> to infinity.  Some lenses have markings indicating the hyper=
focal range for specific <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F-stop" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"F-stop">f-stops</a>, also called a <i>depth-o=
f-field scale</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-49" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth_of_field#cite_note-49"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></div><=
/div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-center" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Contessa_hyperfocal.JPG" cla=
ss=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikiped=
ia/commons/thumb/c/ce/Contessa_hyperfocal.JPG/250px-Contessa_hyperfocal.JPG=
" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"126" class=3D"mw-file-element"=
 data-file-width=3D"1500" data-file-height=3D"753"></a><figcaption>Zeiss Ik=
on Contessa with red marks for hyperfocal distance 20&nbsp;ft at <link rel=
=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r129986063=
2"><span class=3D"fnumber-fallback"><span class=3D"first-letter">f</span>/8=
</span></figcaption></figure>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Near:far_distribution">Near=
:far distribution</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DDepth_of_field&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit sect=
ion: Near:far distribution"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The <abbr title=3D"depth of field">DOF</abbr> beyond the subject is alwa=
ys greater than the <abbr title=3D"depth of field">DOF</abbr> in front of t=
he subject. When the subject is at the hyperfocal distance or beyond, the f=
ar <abbr title=3D"depth of field">DOF</abbr> is infinite, so the ratio is 1=
:=E2=88=9E; as the subject distance decreases, near:far <abbr title=3D"dept=
h of field">DOF</abbr> ratio increases, approaching unity at high magnifica=
tion. For large apertures at typical portrait distances, the ratio is still=
 close to 1:1.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"DOF_formulae">DOF formulae<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDepth_of_fie=
ld&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit section: DOF formulae"=
><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span=
></div>
<p>This section covers some additional formula for evaluating depth of fiel=
d; however they are all subject to significant simplifying assumptions: for=
 example, they assume the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paraxial=
_approximation" title=3D"Paraxial approximation">paraxial approximation</a>=
  of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaussian_optics" title=3D"Gau=
ssian optics">Gaussian optics</a>. They are suitable for practical photogra=
phy, lens designers would use significantly more complex ones.
</p>
